Short answer: start with the existing “econ” dataset and extend it.

Why: It already has county-month coverage with mortgage rates, permits, and income growth—good backbone for affordability metrics. To measure affordability you’ll want to add:
- ACS: median household income (by county)
- HUD FMR: rents (by county/metro)
- Zillow ZHVI/ZORI: home values and asking rents
- Freddie Mac PMMS: mortgage rates (already present)
Optional: property taxes (ACS), insurance proxies, CPI utilities.

Quick next step: Tell me
- geography (nationwide counties, metros, specific states?)
- tenure focus (rent, buy, or both?)
- time span (e.g., 2015–2026?)
I can then extend the “econ” environment to pull ACS, HUD, and Zillow and compute:
- Rent burden (gross rent / income)
- Price-to-income and an HAI-style PITI share (with rate, tax, insurance assumptions)

Want me to proceed with that extension?

